  <article class="entry cf hentry category-a-ha category-a-ha category-90s category-compilation category-pop tag-a-ha tag-headlines-and-deadlines-the-hits-of-a-ha tag-compilation tag-the-hits tag-the-best-of tag-pop-music tag-synth-pop tag-new-wave author-mark-greentree post-type-text article-index-1" id="article-61ef45c74a94625554971021" data-item-id="61ef45c74a94625554971021">

  
    <div class="main-image-wrapper">
      <a href="/musicblog/a-ha-headlines-and-deadlines-the-hits-of-a-ha-compilation-album-review"><div class="main-image content-fill"><img data-src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/565c1ab5e4b05079e4bfa169/1643071147507-J6O53HNSPUTIO1KM0EJT/A-Ha+Headlines+And+Deadlines+The+Best+Of+A-Ha+Compilation+Album+Artwork.jpg" data-image="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/565c1ab5e4b05079e4bfa169/1643071147507-J6O53HNSPUTIO1KM0EJT/A-Ha+Headlines+And+Deadlines+The+Best+Of+A-Ha+Compilation+Album+Artwork.jpg" data-image-dimensions="2500x2479" data-image-focal-point="0.624,0.36271421370967744" alt="A-Ha – Headlines And Deadlines: The Hits Of A-Ha (Compilation Album Review)"  /></div></a>
    </div>
  

    <header class="entry-header cf">

      <p class="entry-actions">
        
        <span class="squarespace-social-buttons inline-style" data-system-data-id="1643071147507-J6O53HNSPUTIO1KM0EJT" data-asset-url="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/565c1ab5e4b05079e4bfa169/1643071147507-J6O53HNSPUTIO1KM0EJT/A-Ha+Headlines+And+Deadlines+The+Best+Of+A-Ha+Compilation+Album+Artwork.jpg" data-record-type="1" data-full-url="/musicblog/a-ha-headlines-and-deadlines-the-hits-of-a-ha-compilation-album-review" data-title="A-Ha – Headlines And Deadlines: The Hits Of A-Ha (Compilation Album Review)"></span>
      </p>

      <p class="entry-more-link"><a href="/musicblog/a-ha-headlines-and-deadlines-the-hits-of-a-ha-compilation-album-review"></a></p>

    </header>
    <div class="entry-title-wrapper">
      <h1 data-content-field="title" class="entry-title">
      
        <a href="/musicblog/a-ha-headlines-and-deadlines-the-hits-of-a-ha-compilation-album-review">A-Ha – Headlines And Deadlines: The Hits Of A-Ha (Compilation Album Review)</a>
      
      </h1>
      <p class="date">
        <time class="published" datetime="2022-01-31">January 31, 2022</time>
      </p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="entry-content">

      
        
          <div class="sqs-layout sqs-grid-12 columns-12" data-layout-label="Post Body" data-type="item" data-updated-on="1643073046066" id="item-61ef45c74a94625554971021"><div class="row sqs-row"><div class="col sqs-col-12 span-12"><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-8f2f548bf3737fff5271"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Released in 1991, <em>Headlines And Deadlines: The Hits of a-ha</em> would take a-ha’s most recognisable works, along with a previously unreleased song, and declare it as their best work to date. While I’ve long considered <a href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/musicblog/2019/1/20/a-ha-hunting-high-and-low-album-review?rq=hunting%20"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>Hunting High &amp; Low</em></span></a><em> </em>to represent some of the very best music in both the synth-pop and new wave eras, only four songs from that incredible debut made it to this 16-track compilation. Nevertheless, an artist’s legacy is a sum of all parts and <em>Headlines And Deadlines </em>showcase just how tight and polished a-ha were as a musical unit throughout their most formative years; but is this really the best of a-ha?</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Prior to examining the selected songs and declaring if this is a collection of songs worthy of a-ha’s greatest creative output, it’s important to note that the streaming editions of <em>Headlines And Deadlines</em> have a different track listing to the physical counterparts. No songs are omitted but they are rearranged meaning that those of you who may have been used to the CD release may find this tracking mildly irritating. It also makes no sense that these variants exist but even more confusing is the fact that the original compilation was billed as <em>The Hits of a-ha! </em>while the streaming editions have been relabelled as <em>The Best of a-ha </em>with the original artwork remaining intact; a trivial variance, yes, but an oddity nonetheless. Add to this the fact that the 2018 vinyl re-issue omits songs, it is fair to say that there isn’t a definitive edition of <em>Headlines And Deadlines</em>, thus sticking with the streaming edition seems like the most logical solution.</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1642999572576_57936"><div class="sqs-block-content"><iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *" frameborder="0" height="900" style="width:100%;max-width:1400px;overflow:hidden;background:transparent;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/au/album/headlines-and-deadline-the-best-of-a-ha/747796629"></iframe></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1643594653131_13334"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Cry Wolf </strong>offers a solid opening to the streaming compilation and is a song that I both love and loathe; yes, dear reader, that is possible! If I’m in the mood to groove and dance then there is nothing better, but if my mood is a little more sombre and serious Cry Wolf then becomes a challenging listen but ultimately fails to change my mood. It is a subjective challenge that I’ve never fully understood but one that I feel compelled to share for music, even that which we love, may not always appeal to us.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Stay On These Roads </strong>is a beautiful song and in some ways, I could see this as a better option for the opening of the streaming editions as it offers a slow burn. Morten Harket's vocal is simply stunning throughout, an instrument in its own right, making this arguably one of his greatest vocal achievements and ensuring that Stay On These Roads is one of my all-time favourite a-ha songs.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>The Blood That Moves The Body </strong>has a <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/artist/grace-jones/32200"><span style="text-decoration:underline">Grace Jones</span></a> feel meaning I love it! Of course, it is 100% a-ha and despite a difficult to interpret lyric, it is most certainly worthy of inclusion here. A brilliant tune!&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Touchy! </strong>is a fun song with a catchy chorus. Sometimes that is all a song needs to be.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>I’ve Been Losing You </strong>may have been a success but I honestly don’t know how it achieved such popularity for I feel it simply isn’t a good song, let alone being single or compilation worthy. Perhaps I’m out of touch with the zeitgeist that surrounded its release but it simply defies logic when reflecting on the music through a modern lens.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Manhattan Skyline </strong>is, arguably, as rock and roll as a-ha<em> </em>has ever been and is a masterful tune that fits perfectly into a-ha’s back catalogue of music. Despite being recorded and released in 1986 it doesn’t sound dated, unlike many other songs from the era.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Crying In The Rain </strong>is a musical masterstroke, from <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/east-of-the-sun-west-of-the-moon/378016648"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>East of the Sun, West of the Moon</em></span></a><em>,</em> with imagery that will make sense to all of us if we care to reflect viscerally.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Early Morning </strong>has a compelling synth element throughout, but it’s largely unforgettable and never really achieved much acclaim as a single in its own right. Subsequently, I question its inclusion here.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>I Call Your Name</strong>, also from<em> East of the Sun, West of the Moon</em> is an enjoyable filler track but as with Early Morning, it fails to captivate the music-centric elements of my soul. Perfect B-side material and enjoyable to listen to, but it isn’t compilation worthy.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Hunting High And Low (Remix) </strong>is, as I’ve said <a href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/musicblog/2019/1/20/a-ha-hunting-high-and-low-album-review?rq=hunting"><span style="text-decoration:underline">before</span></a>, absolutely stunning. I must admit that I wasn’t sold on the Remix, for I believe that compilations should have the original Album or Single version, rather than Medleys, Remixes, or Live performances, but this is one exceptional remix that proves there are exceptions to the rules.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>You Are The One (Remix) </strong>is closely aligned to the original album version and that’s a good thing for it’s a great upbeat tune. The remix in this instance boosts the energy of the song in such a way that I prefer it over the original album mix as heard on <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/stay-on-these-roads/300946993"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>Stay On These Roads</em></span></a>.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Train Of Thought (Remix) </strong>has an addictive rhythm and while I’ve <a href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/musicblog/2019/1/20/a-ha-hunting-high-and-low-album-review?rq=hunting"><span style="text-decoration:underline">previously suggested</span></a> that it has an Elton John (think <a href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/musicblog/2018/6/22/elton-john-victim-of-love-album-review?rq=Elton%20John%20"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>Victim Of Love</em></span></a>) and Grace Jones’ feel, this remix immediately makes me think of <a href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/?category=David+Bowie"><span style="text-decoration:underline">David Bowie</span></a>. Regardless of the influence, or originality, it’s one of the very best songs in a-ha’s back catalogue and another of the remixes that I feel improves the song when compared directly to the original mix.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Move To Memphis</strong>, much like Manhattan Skyline, has a soft rock edge that is thoroughly captivating with a Bowie-inspired sound. It may have been a new tune, but works well against the legacy songs featured on this compilation. Interestingly, Move To Memphis was re-recorded for the 1993 album <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/memorial-beach/62445123"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>Memorial Beach</em></span></a> but is so close to this original that it almost isn’t worth mentioning, except that the re-recording has a little more of a pop-inspired sound which connects the song to their legacy sound signature. Think of it this way, the compilation release is akin to a radio edit while the re-recording is the album version.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>The Living Daylights (Single Version) </strong>is, of course, the theme song from the associated 007 James Bond flick, but it isn’t that good as a song on its own or as a theme song. Comparing the single release to the album version as featured on <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/the-living-daylights-2015-remastered/1044495108?i=1044495999"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>Stay On These Roads</em></span></a>, the latter is much preferred as it is, arguably less James Bond focused meaning it can be better enjoyed as a song in its own right. Naturally, given the purpose of a compilation, it’s logical that the most familiar tune be released but if you get a chance, check out the album version as I’m certain you won’t regret it.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Take On Me, </strong>as I’ve suggested before, isn’t my favourite a-ha tune; it’s simply too campy. Yes, that will likely disappoint those who consider it to be iconic of the new wave era, but the one element that really detracts me is Morten Harket’s high pitched vocal as it’s simply too much and can become headache-inducing.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>The Sun Always Shines On T.V. </strong>is, <a href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/musicblog/2019/1/20/a-ha-hunting-high-and-low-album-review"><span style="text-decoration:underline">as I’ve suggested before</span></a>, a stadium filling tune if there ever was one and it makes for a perfect closing song that encourages playing <em>Headlines And Deadlines </em>again and again.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">There is little doubt that a-ha!<em> </em>represents some of the very best music from the synth-pop and new wave eras and <em>Headlines And Deadlines </em>is one compilation that grows on you the more you listen to it. In the modern era, it could be suggested that a self-curated playlist will always trump a pre-programmed compilation but despite other releases such as <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/the-singles-1984-2004-remastered/368555809"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>The Singles 1984-2004</em></span></a><em>, </em><a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/25-the-very-best-of-a-ha/383431353"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>25: The Very Best of</em></span></a><em>, and</em> <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/album/time-and-again-the-ultimate/1087628947"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><em>Time and Again: The Ultimate</em></span></a>, along with an official <a href="https://music.apple.com/au/playlist/a-ha-essentials/pl.08eb9d068bd1413886c5831dd262d4bc"><span style="text-decoration:underline">Essentials</span></a> playlist, I still find <em>Headlines And Deadlines </em>to be a compelling offering that is the perfect length with the core hits from a-ha that you’ll want to listen to. Yes, there are a few songs that I don’t feel are necessarily worthy of such regard, but when listening to this compilation it is easy to forget that aspect and simply enjoy their collective works. &nbsp;</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block markdown-block sqs-block-markdown" data-block-type="44" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1642999572576_58514"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p data-preserve-html-node="true"><a data-preserve-html-node="true" href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/?category=A-Ha">Check out more a-ha reviews by Subjective Sounds</a></p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1642999572576_59287"><div class="sqs-block-content"><script async src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js"></script>
