      <h1 data-content-field="title" class="entry-title">
      
        <a href="/musicblog/the-flaming-lips-oczy-mlody-album-review">The Flaming Lips – Oczy Mlody (Album Review)</a>
      
      </h1>
      <p class="date">
        <time class="published" datetime="2021-10-21">October 21, 2021</time>
      </p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="entry-content">

      
        
          <div class="sqs-layout sqs-grid-12 columns-12" data-layout-label="Post Body" data-type="item" data-updated-on="1546990189699" id="item-5881531046c3c4aa61c2d8aa"><div class="row sqs-row"><div class="col sqs-col-12 span-12"><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-8d8d5c261d6da7e2ac25"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Experimental rock can be hit or miss, for I detested <a href="https://geo.music.apple.com/us/album/the-dark-side-of-the-moon/346025381?app=music&amp;at=1l3vtbU&amp;itscg=30200&amp;itsct=music_box_link&amp;ls=1"><em>The Flaming Lips and Stardeath and White Dwarfs With Henry Rollins And Peaches Doing The Dark Side Of The Moon</em></a>, yet I found solace in <em>Oczy Mlody</em>; a dichotomy proving that one need not enjoy everything an artist releases.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Released in 2017, <em>Oczy Mlody </em>is The Flaming Lips’ fourteenth studio album and blends experimental rock with a little dream pop that infuses with the listeners’ soul to such an extent that the more you listen to the album, the more difficult it is to not put it on repeat. Add to that the compelling psychedelic artwork and you’ve got yourself an extraordinary piece of musical art that, in my mind at least, talks to the true nature of alternative music in its attempt to challenge what music is and what it can be. &nbsp;</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1635229981020_33382"><div class="sqs-block-content"><iframe src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/oczy-mlody/1164489157?app=music&amp;itsct=music_box_player&amp;itscg=30200&amp;at=1l3vtbU&amp;ls=1" height="730px" frameborder="0" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *;" style="width: 100%; max-width: 1400px; overflow: hidden; border-top-left-radius: 10px; border-top-right-radius: 10px; border-bottom-right-radius: 10px; border-bottom-left-radius: 10px; background-color: transparent;"></iframe></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1635229981020_33449"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Oczy Mlody</strong> as an instrumental-only tune sets the mood for the entire album. It’s atmospheric with an immersive soundstage that tricks the senses as your mind ebb and flows through the soundscape. It’s uplifting while being simultaneously sombre. I love it!</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>How??</strong> starts off beautifully smooth, but while I am a proponent of profanity in music when it is of artistic benefit, I find the first instance of profanity to be disjointed to the overall musicality of the song. Other than that, I would class the song as a vocal and atmospheric masterpiece. The low-bass distortion is particularly pleasing as it doesn’t detract but adds to the depth of the song.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>There Should Be Unicorns</strong> steps up the tempo but retains that gorgeous atmospheric sound. I’m literally held captive by the music, in that special place where we should all be when we are thoroughly enjoying the experience.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Sunrise (Eyes Of The Young)</strong> is perhaps the most experimental track on the album. It shifts direction within the song itself and will appeal to music lovers who appreciate not only musical experimentation but the extreme edges offered by alternative recordings.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Night Nie (Never No)</strong> pans the music from the left and right stereo channels perfectly. You’ll follow the sound around the soundstage as you become immersed in the virtual reality that the artist has created. I adore it, but there are a few audible shocks along the way that prevent you from getting too relaxed.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Galaxy I Sink</strong> is sonically cold, distant and isolating in a manner that is somewhat haunting. I do, however, feel that in this case, the lyrics are superfluous as they become a distracting element in an otherwise excellent composition. While I understand this isn’t the approach they were aiming for, it would be fantastic to have an instrumental-only edition of the album as I feel there are two distinct ways this musical art could be appreciated.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>One Night While Hunting For Faeries And Witches And Wizards To Kill</strong> certainly presents a soundstage that is relatable to the song title. The beat, however, is somewhat predictable and the vocal elements are, again, a slight distraction. It is as though the two elements are simply not co-existing cohesively. Of course, one needs to remember that in the spirit of experimental music, this approach is perfectly acceptable.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Do Glowy</strong> seamlessly continues from the previous track but varies the beat and vocal delivery. The vocals in this instance are purposely auto-tuned a little too far, for my liking, but the style works perfectly with the song and I feel that the vocals are once again in synchronicity with the instrumental elements.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Listening To The Frogs With Demon Eyes</strong> offers another seamless transition but is not as demonic as one would assume, considering the song title. The soundstage is also a little too shallow, compared to the rest of the album, especially in the initial elements of the song. It does open up a couple of minutes into the track, but at over 7 minutes in length, there are several changes that will either appeal or become distracting as you listen to Listening To The Frogs With Demon Eyes. Ultimately, it’s an interesting song as I neither like nor dislike it, it merely exists.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>The Castle</strong>, again, seamlessly transitions between tracks, an aspect I love about listening to <em>Oczy Mlody</em> in the linear album format. Although, I find The Castle to be a little too distorted in the low end and while I’d say that this has been done purposefully, as it is consistent throughout the song, I find it distracting; a shame considering there is a killer song to be heard here.&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>Almost Home (Blisko Domu)</strong> is sonically stunning and is a song that I could listen to for hours on repeat.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><strong>We A Family</strong>, as the final song on <em>Oczy Mlody</em> closes the album out nicely while paying homage to the songs and creativity that has come before it. Even if you decide not to listen to the album again, We A Family will stick with you and ultimately become a memorable musical experience.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">While I haven’t liked every album The Flaming Lips have released, I’m overjoyed that <em>Oczy Mlody </em>isn’t amongst them for it is sonically pleasing and thoroughly enjoyable even if the lyrical meanings remain aloof. It just goes to prove that one needn’t like every album from an artist to be a fan of their work.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block markdown-block sqs-block-markdown" data-block-type="44" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1623221299411_85159"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p data-preserve-html-node="true"><a data-preserve-html-node="true" href="https://www.subjectivesounds.com/index">Check out more reviews by Subjective Sounds</a></p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1623221299411_86091"><div class="sqs-block-content"><script async src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js"></script>
